snippet.textDisplay: You are both such beautiful young ladies and I think it's really wonderful that you are speaking so openly and bringing awareness to this disease. I fully believe that awareness leads to cures because the more exposure it gets the more likely the research will be intensified. I have been in a place where I was dealing with extreme symptoms but had no idea what was going on and some doctors made me feel like I was crazy. That's devastating in itself when you know your own body and you know something isn't right but they can't find anything medically to explain why you're feeling the way you do. In my case it was black mold exposure and I almost died. It was only due to others sharing their experience that I  was finally able to pinpoint the cause. Thank you for sharing your experience and bearing your soul to help others. ❤

God bless you, both. I ended up throwing in the towel and having a hysterectomy for my endo. I tell everyone that it’s like kudzu. It goes and grows wherever it wants and gives zero fucks. I have my miracle daughter who I was told I’d never be able to have.

snippet.textDisplay:
Thank you for being open about this!❤️
I am only 28, and i actually had to remove my uterus just a year back. I had no kids either, so this was a hard message to get.. Several doctors said i had no chance to ever getting pregnant because my uterus was so broken at that point, and the inflammation had spread to other organs as well. So after 5 operations and chemotherapy and high doses of morphine i didn’t think it was worth it anymore!So i really didn’t have a choice... I actually lost my uterus the same month my two best friends became pregnant...
This is one of the toughest things I have gone through, but i’m still positive and not least grateful that I got a new chance. I made the right choice.☺️
I am so grateful for all the good I have in my life, and for me it is much more important to appreciate what you have right now, than worry about what you don’t have. I will never get the chance to have my own kids, but I am forever grateful for my wonderful boyfriend, family and friends that i do have in my life. So i am very lucky, after all❤️. And when a door is closed, another is usually opened and it is a very nice thing to think about ♥ I really wish the both of you the very best! MUCH love from Norway♥️

snippet.textDisplay: I suffered with severe cramps since I first started my period too when I was 11! Going to the doctor and telling them that my cramps are bad and then telling you “just take Motrin” I felt like I was crazy and maybe my cramps are just me imagining them. March 2018 I had this horrible pain (more than usual) and my husband took me to the ER and I was told I needed an emergency surgery cause I had a ruptured cyst that was hemorrhaging and they were scared that it twisted my ovary. That’s when the doctor (who is now my new doctor, love her) told me I have Endo Stage 4. I had to wait til January 2019 to have an excision surgery and I’m so glad I did. I still feel pain but it’s not as bad as before. What I’m struggling with is when I had the excision surgery was that both of my tubes were clogged and she was only able to unclog one. I never thought I would struggle with infertility but here I am. I struggled with it at first but I understand that it’s not my timing yet! Having another excision surgery next year, looking forward to it!  Thank you for sharing you’re story and raising awareness!

I’m not sure whether or not I had endometriosis, but I remember when I was 18, I started having the worst cramping pain while starting my period. It was honestly the worst pain I had ever felt, where I was on the ground, sweating, crying, unable to move, and getting nauseous from the pain. This went on for a few years, until I got the IUD, and since then I have never felt that level of pain.

What I found really frustrating, was when I told my gynecologist about my pain up to that point, she completely shrugged it off and I don’t even think I got a response about it from her. She could have cared less and was very emotionless. Having the right doctor is so important. My IUD procedure with her felt traumatic.

snippet.textDisplay: I'm an RN with endo and I panic when I look at my schedule patterns and don't know exactly when my period will start. I've definitely had to change into surgical scrubs bottoms on multiple occasions from the heavy flow and everyone knows what that means. On the other hand, I'm lucky I work with so many other amazing nurses that totally get it and nothing surprises or grosses anyone out anymore.

I never had endo, but 10 years ago I was dealing with Fibromyalgia and chronic fatigue. My entire body hurt so badly that I could barely walk, and I was afraid to roll over when I was in bed, because I was never sure if changing position would give me a reduction in pain that would make it worth the excruciating pain that I would have to go through to move. Long story short, ALL of my symptoms were related to severe malnutrition from gluten allergy. It took about 6-8 months before I could function. In the meantime, I looked perfectly healthy and no one believed the amount of pain I was in or why I had to sleep for 16 hours per day. Thankfully my family was supportive and helped me a lot with money and doing physical things for me that I couldn’t do. But most people had no sympathy and treated me like I was lazy or crazy. So I completely understand at least the pain aspect of your situations.

The upside of the whole situation for me was that after I was through that, I had empathy for those around me with pain issues. So I could be that person who understood when someone else was suffering. I could be the person for someone else that I wish I had had when I was in that situation.
